This is a companion to \emph{Spider Cipher Theory} and uses its
notation: \(Z_{40}\) is the integers modulo \(40\), \(S_{40}\) the
arrangements of \(Z_{40}\), \(e = [ 0,1,...,39]\) the
sorted deck, \(t^{c}\) the cut at index \(c\), \(b_{i,j}\) the swap of
the cards at indexes \(i\) and \(j\), and {[}count down by odds, then up
by evens{]}

\(s = [ 39,37,35,33,31,...,9,7,5,3,1,0,2,4,6,8,...30,32,34,36,38]\)

the back-front shuffle. Composition is read right to left, so
\(s \circ t^{c}\) is a cut at \(c\) followed by a back-front shuffle.
Cycle notation \((a\ b\ c)\) means the permutation that sends \(a\) to
\(b\), \(b\) to \(c\), \(c\) to \(a\), and fixes everything else.

Facts written as FACTS(Name) are verified by the computer test suite in
\texttt{src/spider\_cipher\_facts.c}; each one re-checks on every build.

\hypertarget{the-perfect-shuffle}{%
\chapter{The Perfect Shuffle}\label{the-perfect-shuffle}}

The plain spider pseudo-shuffle has a short cycle:

\((s \circ t^{2})^{9} = e\)

Nine shuffles at cut index \(2\) return the deck exactly to where it
started, as demonstrated in FACTS(IReachable). Over all cut indexes, the
first return to a cut of the starting deck takes at least \(9\) steps,
and \(9\) is achieved.

Nine is far below what counting permits. The number of distinct
shuffle words of length at most \(30\) is
\((40^{31} - 1)/39 > 40! = \# S_{40}\), while for length at most
\(29\) it is less than \(40!\). So collisions among shuffle words can
not be forced before length \(30\), and a cycle floor of \(30\) is the
best that any family of \(40\) single-card-swap variants of this shape
could hope for.

The perfect spider shuffle adds one swap after the back-front shuffle:

\(q = b_{0,19} \circ s\)

The perfect spider graph has the same vertices \(V = S_{40}\) and, for
each vertex \(v\), the \(40\) outgoing edges
\(v \rightarrow q \circ t^{c} \circ v\).

With this one change the cycle floor rises from \(9\) to \(30\), one
step from the counting bound: for every cut index \(c\), the first
return of \((q \circ t^{c})^{k}\) to any cut of the starting deck takes
at least \(30\) steps. This is verified for all \(40\) cut indexes in
FACTS(Cycles), and the distinctness of all short shuffle words is
verified to depth \(6\) in FACTS(PerfectNeighborhood6).

\hypertarget{the-human-form}{%
\section{The Human Form}\label{the-human-form}}

Swapping the cards at indexes \(0\) and \(19\) after the shuffle sounds
like a job for a machine: nobody wants to count \(19\) cards into a
deck, twice, without error. But the same permutation has a second form:

\(b_{0,19} \circ s = s \circ b_{1,39}\)

To see this, read the placement off the shuffle \(s\): the back-front
shuffle delivers the card at index \(1\) (the second card) to index
\(19\), and the card at index \(39\) (the bottom card) to index \(0\).
So swapping indexes \(0\) and \(19\) after the shuffle is the same as
swapping indexes \(1\) and \(39\) before it. This identity is verified
on evolving decks for every cut index in FACTS(PerfectHumanForm).

The perfect shuffle is therefore the procedure:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Cut the deck.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Swap the second card with the bottom card.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Back-front shuffle.
  \end{quote}
\end{enumerate}

No counting to \(19\) is ever required. The second card and the bottom
card are the two easiest cards to locate in a deck after the top card
itself.

\hypertarget{perfect-spider-graph-is-vertex-invariant}{%
\chapter{Perfect Spider Graph is Vertex
Invariant}\label{perfect-spider-graph-is-vertex-invariant}}

The proof is the same as for the plain spider graph. Every edge composes
a fixed permutation \(q \circ t^{c}\) on the left, so relabeling all the
vertices \(x\) by composing on the right, \(x \rightarrow x \circ (w^{- 1} \circ v)\),
makes vertex \(w\) look like vertex \(v\) and relabels all the edges
consistently. Nothing in the argument depends on which fixed
permutations the edges use.

As before, this means no amount of observing movement through the graph
reveals the starting point, and the structure of the graph can be
studied from any single vertex.

\hypertarget{perfect-spider-graph-is-fully-connected}{%
\chapter{Perfect Spider Graph is Fully
Connected}\label{perfect-spider-graph-is-fully-connected}}

Every vertex reaches every other vertex:
\(B_{\infty}(v) = S_{40}\). So restricting play to the reachable set
costs nothing; the active state space really is \(40!\).

The proof follows the same plan as for the plain spider graph, with
computer-verified waypoints. The plain proof leaned on the \(9\)-cycle
\((s \circ t^{2})^{9} = e\) at every turn -- the very cycle the perfect
shuffle exists to destroy -- so the perfect proof must fish with
different bait: it rides \emph{plain} cycles with \emph{perfect}
shuffles and keeps what washes back.

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  By vertex invariance we need only show \(B_{\infty}(e) = S_{40}\).
  A path \(e \rightarrow \cdot \cdot \cdot \rightarrow v\) means
  \(v = (q \circ t^{c_{p - 1}}) \circ \cdot \cdot \cdot \circ (q \circ t^{c_{0}})\)
  for some sequence of cuts, so each reachable \(v\) is shorthand for a
  sequence of cuts usable in any path.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(e\) and \(q^{- 1}\) are reachable. Choosing \(c = 0\) repeatedly
  reaches \(q^{k}\) for all \(k > 0\), and \(q\) has order \(36\):
  \(q^{36} = e\). So \(e\) is reachable as a cycle and
  \(q^{- 1} = q^{35}\) is reachable.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(e\) reaches every cut: \(t^{a} = q^{35} \circ (q \circ t^{a})\).
  In words: take one step at cut \(a\), then \(35\) steps at cut
  \(0\); the shuffle-and-swap parts cancel and only the cut survives.
  Verified for all \(40\) cuts in FACTS(PerfectCuts).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Trail fishing. For any swap \(b\) and any permutation \(w\),
  \(b \circ w = w \circ (w^{- 1} \circ b \circ w)\), and
  \(w^{- 1} \circ b \circ w\) is again a swap. So running the letters of
  a \emph{plain} cycle with \emph{perfect} shuffles pushes all the
  \(b_{0,19}\) factors through to one side, where they collect as a
  product of swaps -- the plain part vanishes entirely. The plain
  spider fact \((s \circ t^{39})^{24} = e\) (FACTS(InverseCycles))
  therefore lifts to a pure product of \(24\) swaps:

  \(f = (q \circ t^{39})^{24} = (4\ 38\ 17\ 19\ 29\ 30\ 35)\)

  a \(7\)-cycle, verified in FACTS(PerfectFish).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(e\) reaches a \(3\)-cycle. The translate
  \(\bar{f} = t^{- 1} \circ f \circ t\) is reachable (cuts, then the
  fish, then cuts), and its support meets the support of \(f\) in
  exactly one card. Two cycles that share exactly one point have a
  \(3\)-cycle commutator:

  \(g = \bar{f}^{6} \circ f^{6} \circ \bar{f} \circ f = (30\ 35\ 31)\)

  using \(f^{6} = f^{- 1}\) since \(f\) is a \(7\)-cycle. Verified in
  FACTS(Perfect3Cycle).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(e\) reaches \(a = (0\ 1\ 2)\). Conjugating by reachable elements
  keeps things reachable, and with \(H = t^{- 1} \circ q^{- 1} \circ t^{2} \circ q^{2}\),

  \(a = H \circ g \circ H^{- 1} = (0\ 1\ 2)\)

  which is a single composition anyone can verify by hand or machine.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(e\) reaches every consecutive \(3\)-cycle
  \(a_{i} = t^{- i} \circ a \circ t^{i} = (i\ \ i \oplus 1\ \ i \oplus 2)\),
  where \(\oplus\) is \(+\) modulo \(40\).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(e\) reaches the adjacent swap \(b_{0,1}\). The odd cut \(t\)
  composed with \(19\) consecutive \(3\)-cycles is exactly one swap:

  \(b_{0,1} = t \circ a_{2}^{- 1} \circ a_{4}^{- 1} \circ \cdot \cdot \cdot \circ a_{38}^{- 1}\)

  where \(a_{i}^{- 1} = a_{i}^{2}\) is reachable. (Equivalently:
  \(b_{0,1} \circ t^{- 1}\) is a \(39\)-cycle, and an odd-length cycle
  is a chain of \(3\)-cycles through every other point.)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(e\) reaches every swap, exactly as in the plain proof:
  \(b_{i,i \oplus 1} = t^{- i} \circ b_{0,1} \circ t^{i}\); then
  \(b_{0,j} = b_{j - 1,j} \circ b_{0,j - 1} \circ b_{j - 1,j}\) by
  induction; then \(b_{i,j} = t^{- i} \circ b_{0,j - i} \circ t^{i}\).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(e\) reaches \(S_{40}\). Any arrangement can be sorted by swaps;
  applying the inverse swaps to \(e\) produces it.
  \end{quote}
\end{enumerate}

As an independent cross-check, a stabilizer-chain (Schreier--Sims)
computation of the group generated by
\(\{ q \circ t^{c}\}\) gives order exactly \(40!\).

\hypertarget{free-depth-and-the-birthday-bound}{%
\chapter{Free Depth and the Birthday
Bound}\label{free-depth-and-the-birthday-bound}}

Connectivity says every deck is reachable. The finer question, the one
that governs entropy capture, is how long the spider graph keeps
distinct paths distinct.

The \emph{free depth} \(r\) is the largest \(r\) such that all distinct
cut sequences of length at most \(r\) produce distinct decks. While the
tree is free, each step contributes \(\log_{2}40 \simeq 5.32\) bits of
path entropy faithfully; the first coincidence is the first time two
different histories become indistinguishable in the state.

Three quantities now separate. The \emph{cycle floor} is the shortest
first return of a single repeated cut. The \emph{girth} is the shortest
word of cuts equal to the identity. The free depth obeys
\(r \leq girth\), since an identity word of length \(L\) makes the word
of length \(L + 1\) that appends one more cut collide with that single
cut. For the plain spider, \((s \circ t^{2})^{9} = e\) forces
\(r \leq 9\). But nothing forces collisions to come from cycles at all.

\hypertarget{the-collapse-need-not-meet-at-the-identity}{%
\section{The Collapse Need Not Meet at the
Identity}\label{the-collapse-need-not-meet-at-the-identity}}

One would like to prove that the shortest collision factors through a
cycle -- that two colliding walks must, in effect, meet at the
identity -- because then the verified cycle floor would bound the free
depth and no neighborhood search would be needed.

It is false. In the \(10\)-card perfect model (the same construction
with \(Z_{10}\), swap of indexes \(0\) and \(4\)), the cut words

\(9,3,9,3\) and \(0,1,7,2,0\)

reach the same deck. This is a collision at depth \(5\), while the
girth of that graph is \(6\) and a cycle-induced collision needs
length \(girth + 1 = 7\). The collapse is a theta -- two paths
diverging and re-meeting away from the identity -- and no cycle
analysis can see it. This witness, with the exact floors, free depths,
and girths of the \(10\)- and \(12\)-card models, is verified in
FACTS(FreeDepthTen) and FACTS(FreeDepthTwelve).

\hypertarget{the-birthday-law}{%
\section{The Birthday Law}\label{the-birthday-law}}

What actually ends freeness is counting. The depth-\(r\) tree holds
\(40^{r}\) words mapping into \(40!\) decks, and coincidences among
them become unavoidable near \(40^{2r} \approx 40!\), that is,

\(r^{*} = \frac{1}{2}\log_{40}(40!) \approx 15.\)

The small models confirm that the free depth sits at this birthday
line no matter where the cycle floor is:

\begin{quote}
\begin{tabular}{rlrrr}
\(n\) & shuffle & floor & free depth \(r\) & \(\frac{1}{2}\log_{n}(n!)\) \\
\hline
10 & plain   & 4  & 3 & 3.3 \\
10 & perfect & 6  & 4 & 3.3 \\
12 & plain   & 6  & 5 & 4.0 \\
12 & perfect & 10 & 5 & 4.0 \\
14 & plain   & 6  & 5 & 4.8 \\
14 & perfect & 6  & 5 & 4.8 \\
\end{tabular}
\end{quote}

The floors wander from \(4\) to \(10\); the free depths track the last
column. (The observed first collisions even arrive somewhat later than
independent random sampling would predict -- the tree's shared
prefixes mildly suppress coincidences -- so the walk is no worse than
random, and slightly better.)

\hypertarget{consequences-for-the-design}{%
\section{Consequences for the
Design}\label{consequences-for-the-design}}

The birthday law assigns the cycle floor its true job: \emph{stay
above the birthday line so that cycles never bind before statistics
do}. For \(40\) cards the line is at about \(15\).

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Plain spider has floor \(9 < 15\): it is cycle-bound, with
  \(r \leq 9\). Its own algebra cuts it down before counting does.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Perfect spider has floor \(30 > 15\): it is birthday-bound, with
  expected free depth near \(15\) -- about \(80\) bits of faithfully
  captured path entropy -- and below that depth the expected collision
  mass \(40^{2r}/(2 \cdot 40!)\) is negligible.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  No shuffle of any design can exceed the birthday line. The perfect
  shuffle therefore gives up nothing: it converts the binding
  constraint from a repairable design flaw into a law of counting.
  \end{quote}
\end{enumerate}

What is certified for \(40\) cards: all words of length at most \(6\)
are distinct (FACTS(PerfectNeighborhood6), an exhaustive search of
about four billion decks), so \(r \geq 6\). Each further level costs a
factor of \(40\); certifying the expected \(r \approx 15\) by
exhaustion is out of reach, and the small-model law is the honest
evidence that the perfect spider walk behaves like a random one. The
collisions that eventually end freeness are statistical, not
structural -- which is exactly the property a cipher wants.

\hypertarget{why-not-swap-first-and-last}{%
\chapter{Why Not Swap First and
Last}\label{why-not-swap-first-and-last}}

There is a neighboring variant that looks just as good and is easier to
guess: swap the \emph{first and last} cards after the shuffle,

\(\hat{q} = b_{0,39} \circ s = s \circ b_{38,39}\)

which in human form is ``swap the bottom two cards, then shuffle'' --
one card away from the perfect shuffle's ``swap the second card with the
bottom card.'' It was implemented at one point in this project. It is
wrong, and this chapter records why, so it is not explored again.

\hypertarget{six-shuffles-return-the-deck}{%
\section{Six shuffles return the
deck}\label{six-shuffles-return-the-deck}}

\((\hat{q} \circ t^{4})^{6} = e\)

Six shuffles at cut index \(4\) return the deck \emph{exactly} to where
it started. The cycle floor is \(6\): worse than the plain spider's
\(9\), and a factor of five below the perfect shuffle's \(30\).
Verified in FACTS(FirstLastCycleFloor).

The floor matters because returning to (a cut of) the starting deck
repeats pad structure. The security story depends on the deck making
long excursions through \(S_{40}\) between any such coincidences; the
counting bound permits excursions of length \(30\), the perfect shuffle
achieves \(30\), and the first/last swap squanders the entire margin.

\hypertarget{nine-shuffles-are-one-swap}{%
\section{Nine shuffles are one
swap}\label{nine-shuffles-are-one-swap}}

\((\hat{q} \circ t^{2})^{9} = b_{1,39}\)

Nine shuffles at cut index \(2\) amount to swapping two cards and
changing nothing else, as verified in FACTS(FirstLastFish). A cipher
step is supposed to scramble; here nine of them barely stir the deck.

The mechanism is the trail fishing of the connectivity proof, working
against the variant. The plain pseudo-shuffle \(s \circ t^{2}\) has
orbits of sizes \(9,9,9,9,3\) with the fixed card \(38\), and its lone
\(3\)-orbit is \(\{ 0,1,39\}\). The trail of a swap rides
the orbits of its two endpoints. The first/last swap \(b_{0,39}\) has
\emph{both} endpoints inside the \(3\)-orbit, so its nine-swap trail
wraps a three-card track and collapses to a single swap. The perfect
swap \(b_{0,19}\) places only one endpoint there -- index \(19\) rides
a \(9\)-orbit -- so its trails spread across the deck instead of
collapsing.

\hypertarget{the-record}{%
\section{The Record}\label{the-record}}

The first/last graph is, for what it is worth, still fully connected:
its nine-shuffle swap \(b_{1,39}\) is itself the first rung of a
complete swap ladder, verified in FACTS(FirstLastCuts),
FACTS(FirstLastAdjacent), and FACTS(FirstLastSwaps). Connectivity is its
only virtue.

The lesson, recorded so this ground is not plowed twice: the cycle
floor is the gate. Any candidate variant of the spider shuffle must
first demonstrate its floor over all \(40\) cut indexes -- as
FACTS(Cycles) does for the perfect shuffle and
FACTS(FirstLastCycleFloor) does for this rejected one -- before any
other property earns attention. A variant that fails the gate fails,
no matter how natural the procedure feels in the hands.

